title: Printrbot LC+ Heated Bed Clips Side & Front

description.text: Before I got my glass plate I noticed the bed on my LC+ wasn't staying flat as it heated up so I made these clips to help flatten it by clamping the edges. It took four Side Clips and one Front Clip.

If your calibration is correct these should just slide over the birch deck and meet the heated bed flush at the edge. Start by sliding the clips up to the edge -not flush- but rotated slightly to start one corner of a clip while simultaneously giving it a slight whack with the back of a screwdriver; it should climb onto the bed, then you can push the rest of the clip flush & position. The spines of the Side Clips are designed shallow to just clear the Z-Rod assemblies on either side of the moving bed. The Front Clip is deeper & wider (so you only need one) and has a thicker spine to compensate for the longer reach so it won't work on the sides. Edit 8/18/2012:
The original clips were a bit tight so I made improved set (v2) and shaved 5% off the upper bite. I recommend trying these first. Place the forward side clips 65mm (2.5") back from the front edge of the table. Press the Y HOME button and adjust clips slightly so their back edge just misses the Z-Rod assemblies. Likewise bring the table forward & place the rear side clips equidistant from the back edge of the hot bed ~41.5mm (1 5/8"). Front Clip v2 has also been shaved 5% & corrected by Netfab so there are no non-manifold issues using Slic3r. I used a 75% infill so they won't crack. If you print a fat first layer, don't forget to trim the leftover flashing from that layer before trying to mount the clips, else they'll fight you on one side.

description.text:
Mat board push cutter, similar to a Logan push style bevel cutter. The cutting angle is set to 52 degrees and it was designed to cut 4 ply mat board (~1/16"). There are 7 unique parts to this build, two being 3D printed parts, a razor blade, melt-in style nuts, and 3 different sized #4-40 screws. If someone wanted me to redesign the cutter with smaller holes that could be tapped or used with self-tapping screws I'd be happy to do so. Also I could make the unit cut thicker (say 8 ply 1/8") mat board, which I plan to do if I ever get some thick mat but I'll make that a new part designation as I want the centered cutting mark on the units back to reflect the true cutting point.

To assemble: Clean up all the edges of the printed parts and press in the #4-40 nuts using a fine tipped soldering iron. Nuts should be flush or slightly below the surface. File down any plastic that is pushed above the back surface and also re-tap the threads to remove any plastic that gets into the nut's lower threads (or just use shorter screws than listed). Attached the base and the blade holder using the #4-40 X 1/2" screw as shown. Torque screw down till a fair amount of resistance is needed to rotate the blade holder, you'll need to use you own judgement here. You can put a ever-so-little dab of Loc-Tite on the screw but don't let it come into contact with the plastic as it could cause the plastic to get brittle and crank over time. Install the blade onto the blade holder and set the correct cutting depth by adjusting the set-screw on the bottom or the base. The tip of the blade should be just below the bottom surface of the material to be cut. Then start cutting or watch a Logan mat cutter tutorial video on Youtube.

description.text:
This cyclonic separator is my first THING so be nice. I was wanting to buy a cyclonic separator but couldn't find anything for less the $70 so I took a look on Thingiverse and saw some rudimentary separators. They weren't quite what I wanted so I threw something together real quick. The infeed and outfeed are sized for standard 1.25" hose. I'll eventually upgrade to a larger hose. I added a couple of specific features:
1) Mathematical dimensions based on the
"Puu-0_4400_cyclone_calculation_sheet.xls" spreadsheet from Neil Stone
2) Added an input feed down ramp to remove the turbulent dead zone introduced by the infeed.
3) Broke the design into three pieces(bottom, top, and outfeed), with separation between the pieces for simple glue together assembly.
4) Added a support to the bottom to ease mounting the cyclone to a 5 gallon bucket or similar. Required Additional Hardware:
4 - Size 10 Bolts
4 - Size 10 Nuts
8 - Size 10 Washers This design printed well on my Prusa I3 and has been eating all my table saw(building a shoe bench) can put out for the last couple of weeks.

1) Print the three separate parts
2) Mount the Outfeed tube to the top piece by pushing through the hole in the upper surface of the top. Try not to sand the piece much here, it is meant to be a tight fit.
3) Use the Bottom piece to mark a hole in the top of paint bucket and cut out the dump hole in the bucket lid. Line up the bottom piece on the dump hole and mark/drill the four mounting holes. Mount the bottom piece due the bucket using the additional hardware. Make sure bucket lid is tight on bucket
4) Mount the Top/Outfeed assembly to the bottom with a small bead of super glue, let dry
4) Mount shopvac hose to outfeed(top port) using a ziptie/tape/or similar. Mount your input hose to the infeed(side port)
5) Suck away

description.text: This is a part that I designed to help make mounting receiver antennas to the Shrieker. It's meant to run the antennas up through the two holes in the back, then just push a small zip tie (tapered end first) into the holes to create a tight fit. Small needle nose pliers help with getting them in nice and tight, just be sure to grab only the zip tie with your pliers. Then cut the tie to length and secure the antennas to the ties with heat shrink. I've used this mount on many Shrieker builds and it works great.

This is simple all in one spool holder for mounting above a Wooden Laser Cut Prusa I3 Frame. It uses a 3/8" crossbar threaded through the risers and reel captures. I also included a printable threaded rod and nut for the adventurous. The reel capture should work with most reels and the risers mount to any 0.25" sheet, plywood or otherwise. Additional Hardware:
1) 1 - 3/8" Threaded (length as required)
2) 2 - 3/8" Nuts
3) 4 - 3/8" Washers

1) Print all the pieces, Drill out holes with a 3/8" drill bit.
2) Slide one riser onto your Prusa I3 frame, insert 3/8"threaded rod through riser, a 3/8"washer and put 1 reel capture onto threaded rod
3) Add your reel and a second reel capture, another 3/8" washer then add the second riser.
4) Add a 3/8" washer to either side of the 3/8"rod and then a nut to secure, tighten and align to preference.

title: Automatic water-filler for solar fountain WIP

description.text: I made a solar fountain for my deck one year ago, but it keeps running dry as the water evaporates. This my WIP to build a automated filling system for the fountain. It will be plumbed into the garden drip system, so it will fill during the time the sprinklers/drip feed runs. Basically inside the tube is a table tennis ball. As water rise the ball floats and shuts off the flow. This way the fountain should get topped up as needed. This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://tinkercad.com/things/afJaXz9ZcRJ

This thing was made with Tinkercad. It comes in two parts, the tube and the dome top. I lined inside the dome  with plumbers putty, then pushed in a table tennis ball to get a nice smooth fit. I then  glued the tube and the dome together. There is a hole in the top of the dome where I glued in a drip irrigation connector.  
As I stated this is a WIP as I have not had chance to connect it  to the drip feed yet and test it out. I will post the results later.

description.text:
Upon initial print of KKors leatherman sheath, I had some fitment issues. Whilst this may have been able to be cleared up with some scaling, I didn't want to spend time adjusting the print.

WaveSupportApparatus has a model that includes modular attachment sections on the sides of the sheath. While I'm not a huge fan of them, the model fits the tool well, so I started working on a hybrid.

I modified WaveSupportApparatus's modular leatherman holster to remove the modularity. I then attached the G2 pen holder from KKor's work. This is a right side only holster with a 45 degree forward cant, with the pen mount riding at the back of the sheath. I noticed with the pen in the front, there was less concealment available so it was moved to the back.

title: Princess Zelda Tiara (Windwaker)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
So I just completed Windwaker with the kids, and I thought I'd model out Zelda's tiara for my 3 year old. Most of you have probably seen the Master sword I made for my son (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2666232).

Once I printed these, I just hot-glued some DIY barrettes on the back of each part so they clip into her hair at the appropriate points. The orientation of the wing parts prints with some pretty noticable layer lines, but if you stand them up and print them vertically they print better on the backside, but take about 4 hours at .1mm layer height. That being said, using enamel paints like I did requires no sanding.

The front tiara piece I printed upside down like it is, it offers the best layer adhesion for the support in cura that way.

Painting

I just used some basic Testors enamle paints to make the parts the colors that I wanted them. I didn't have any white or red filament at the time, so I just went with paint. The yellow part I just left yellow. I considered painting it gold but opted not to.

description.text:

I've posted two needle sizes (5mm and 6mm) and two overall lengths (230mm and 285mm) . On the 230mm length set, I can easily do 30 stitches and maybe even get down to 25. Let me know if you have another size you'd like and I'll add to the collection.

UPDATE: I've beefed up the connecting cord - it is a little stiffer (and a lot stronger) but still fairly natural to knit with.

description.text:
Joiners to construct a buckyball from sticks or tubes.
A buckyball only needs one kind of joiner and one kind of rod.
Two sizes are posted here. One takes 6mm rods and one takes 3mm.
The parts could be scaled up to make large structures but it would be an expensive exercise.
A complete set of 60 3mm joiners needs about 100 grams of plastic.
Printed at .4mm layers they take about 5 minutes each.
For 6mm parts multiply that by a factor of eight.
For 12mm multiply by eight again.
A set of 3mm might cost $3 - 6mm $24, 12mm - $190 and 24mm $1500.

I posted the joiners in pairs to improve packing when printing many at once. Each joiner in at the junction of two hexagons and one pentagon.
The orientation of the joiner must be correct to form the ball. It would not be obvious which way is correct so I've add some guides.
There is an arrow on the bottom which point to the pentagon. The arrow can be hard to see on some prints so I also added a little pointer to the perimeter of the base.
I've printed them at both .4 and .2mm - both work.
Prints at .2mm look a little better but it probably isn't worth the extra time.
I'm printing the 3mm parts 12 at once. The print bed isn't full and I could probably double that, The holes are cleaned up using a drill.
3mm OD bamboo skewers cut to length work fairly well with the 3mm joiner. Drinking straws work with the larger joiners but not good for anything meant to last. I've also found they print OK at 3/4 scale and this is a good size for use with match sticks. For mine I used skews cut to 100mm lengths. You could make them much longer or shorter as required.
The ball diameter is approximately 5 times the stick length
There are 90 stick so the total length of edges is about 18 times the diameter. I've included a .stl of a ball for reference. I think the easiest way to assemble in the start be turning the sticks and joiner into pentagons - make sure the arrow point in and the flats are all on the same side.
Then join the pentagons together with sticks. As long as no pentagons are flipped (ie flats on the wrong side) it should turn into a ball.

comments.text:
I'm not sure I can make it much clearer.
As I said - make the pentagons first.
Lay five parts in a circle with the arrows pointing in and join them up.
Repeat till you have 12 pentagons. As long as you don't flip a pentagon or bend a stick into an un-natural angle there is only one way to join them up.

description.text:
Tool to check if your laser hits the middle of your lens.
This can help you align the machine better, to know where the beam hit your lens. If it hits on the edge anywhere its time to fix the alignment.

Contains both STL file for 3D printing, aswell as DXF files if you want to cut it in acrylic - see instructions how to use below.
STL file is a bit rough at the moment - changes coming up.

Instructions:

1: Cut the file in 2mm (or what you have) acrylic/wood, or 3D print it
2: Glue the two pieces together (only if you cut it)

How to use:

Put a piece of tape on the side with the smaller hole.
Put the tool around your laser head, keep it in place when you test-fire. Please, look away when doing this.
Remove the tool and look at the tape to see in the smaller circle where the laser dot hit.
Do this in all four corners and in the middle of the machine.

The small notches can be used if you want to use rubber bands to fasten the tool to the head when using it to keep the lid closed.
This is for the regular K40.

Does not work on air assist nozzles.

For a complete mirror alignment guide - check out this URL: https://k40laser.se/lens-mirrors/k40-mirror-alignment-and-leveling/

The IoT Sentry is the Challenge submission for the Z-Wave Smart Home Maker Challenge that was sponsored by Make and Sigma Designs.

The IoT Sentry is an indoor/outdoor monitoring solution based on off-the-shelf Z-Wave products. It is meant to integrate with a Z-Wave compatible gateway and use online service providers, such as IFTTT, to trigger actions. It was designed to house the following Z-Wave devices.

  • Fibaro Motion Sensor
  • Fibaro Flood Sensor
  • First Alert Smoke Detector

PLA was used to print all of the pieces.

The motion sensor is held in place within the motion sensor housing using the sensor’s included mounting screw. The face of the motion sensor is attached with a 3x20mm cap head screws.

The motion sensor head unit is attached to the Sentry housing through the use of the sensor bar at the bottom and a nut/bolt passing through the two pieces.

The smoke detector is attached within the housing using the detector’s included wall mounting bracket and screws.

The leak detector currently is held in place at the bottom of the housing using wire as I need to still create a mounting bracket.

The pole mount should be printed with at least 20% infill. It uses 1/4” bolts, washers, and nuts. The pole mount is meant to be mounted onto 1/2” EMT.

If the housing is printed in two parts, I used an epoxy adhesive to attach the two pieces.

Print the test piece. Stop the print when noticeable warping (object ends lift more than one layer height) is seen. Measure how high the object is.
The image shows three tests made using Orbi-Tech's polycarbonate at 300 C, on 110 C Kapton tape bed primed with dilute ABS juice, 0.225 mm layer height and 2.0 W/T setting, Slic3r 0.8.3.
The leftmost part was printed with 50 mm/s speed, 4 perimeters and 0.3 fill density.
The middle part is the same, but with 25 mm/s speed.
The rightmost part is again at 50 mm/s speed, but with 2 perimeters and 0.2 fill density.

title: Trammel of Archimedes, Snap, Ellipsograph, Ellipse, Math, Model

description.text:
All children should have one of these for pondering over mathematics, I think.

The trammel of Archimedes is an interesting geometric structure for constructing ellipses or exploring simple and appealing mathematical relations. It is fairly easy to design in Fusion 360 or any other 3D design environment. It requires a bit of the Pythagorean Theorem if one wants to be accurate; it further allows students to play with elliptical curves. How do we know the curve so drawn is an ellipse?

In this design, I made the sliders (or shuttles) fairly loose for easy installation. There are two types of sliders here for smooth assembly. The sliders can be either snapped into the arm or fastened using caps (with a drop of glue if necessary).

I also designed the handle to accommodate a school pencil (up to a diameter 8.5mm) so that one can either turn the handle around for fun or insert a pencil and do some real drawing!

Of course, one can just use a handle-less bar and make a fidget toy--soothing and mind-entertaining.

If any joint feels tight after assembly (depending on printer settings), a drop of lubricant will certainly help.

References:

  1. Trammel of Archimedes. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trammel_of_Archimedes
  2. Ellipsographs: Do-nothing machines that do so much!
    http://americanhistory.si.edu/blog/ellipsographs
